an  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"Beatrix","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Late Latin personal name, which was borne by a saint martyred in Rome, together with Saints Faustinus and Simplicius, in the early 4th century. The original form of the name was probably <i>Viatrix</i>, a feminine version of <i>Viator</i> ‘voyager (through life)’, which was a favourite name among early Christians. This was then altered by association with Latin <i>Beatus</i> ‘blessed’ (<i>Via-</i> and <i>Bea-</i> sometimes being pronounced the same in Late Latin).  See also  Beatrice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Beatrix von Hohenstauffen was born in 1152, in Holy Roman Empire, her father, Friedrich I. 'Barbarossa' römisch-deutscher Kaiser, was 30 and her mother, Adela von Vohburg, was 30. She had at least 1 daughter with Guillaume II Count de Chalon-sur-Saone. She died about 1174, in Chalon-sur-Saône, Saône-et-Loire, Burgundy, France, at the age of 23, and was buried in Lorch, Ostalbkreis, Baden-Württemberg, Germany."},"et":{"1152–about 1174":"1152–umbes 1174","1152–1174":"1152–1174","1140–1202":"1140–1202","1096–1171":"1096–1171","1170–1227":"1170–1227","1122–1190":"1122–1190","1122–1187":"1122–1187","1190":"1190","1187":"1187","1152":"1152","1174":"1174","1096":"1096","1140":"1140","1171":"1171","1170":"1170","1227":"1227","um 1170":"umbes 1170","1147":"1147","1202":"1202","1122":"1122","about 1174":"umbes 1174","Chalon-sur-Saône, Saône-et-Loire, Burgundy, France":"Chalon-sur-Saône, Saône-et-Loire, Bourgogne, Prantsusmaa","Thiers, Puy-de-Dôme, Auvergn